**I. POLICY STATEMENT**

Sapphos Environmental Inc. (\"Sapphos\" or \"the Company\") is committed
to providing a workplace free from discrimination, harassment, and
retaliation. Every employee, applicant, contractor, intern, and
volunteer has the right to work in an environment where they are treated
with dignity and respect.

**Sapphos Environmental Inc. strictly prohibits all forms of unlawful
discrimination, harassment (including sexual harassment), and
retaliation.**

This prohibition applies to all aspects of employment and covers conduct
by employees, supervisors, managers, clients, vendors, contractors, and
any other third parties with whom employees interact in connection with
their work.

**Violations of this policy will result in appropriate disciplinary
action, up to and including termination of employment.**

The Company encourages all employees to report any conduct that violates
this policy. **Retaliation against anyone who reports harassment,
participates in an investigation, or opposes unlawful practices is
strictly prohibited and will result in disciplinary action.**

This policy is established in accordance with the California Fair
Employment and Housing Act (Gov. Code § 12900 et seq.) and applicable
federal law.

**II. SCOPE AND COVERAGE**

**A. Who Is Protected**

This policy protects:

-   **All employees** (full-time, part-time, temporary, seasonal,
    probationary)

-   **Job applicants**

-   **Interns and trainees**

-   **Volunteers**

-   **Independent contractors and consultants**

-   **Former employees** (for retaliation protections)

**B. Where This Policy Applies**

This policy applies to conduct occurring:

-   **At Company premises** (offices, field sites, laboratories, project
    locations)

-   **At Company-related events** (conferences, training sessions,
    business meetings, social functions, team-building activities)

-   **During business travel** (hotels, restaurants, transportation,
    client sites)

-   **In virtual/remote work environments** (video calls, email, instant
    messaging, collaboration platforms, company intranet)

-   **Off-site when work-connected** (client entertainment, professional
    networking events)

-   **On social media** when interactions are work-related or involve
    coworkers

**C. Third-Party Conduct**

Sapphos is committed to protecting employees from harassment
by **non-employees** (clients, vendors, subcontractors, consultants,
regulatory agency personnel) and prohibits harassment **of
non-employees** by Sapphos employees.

Employees who experience harassment by third parties should report it
immediately using the reporting procedures in Section V. The Company
will take appropriate action, which may include discontinuing business
relationships with third parties who engage in harassment.

**III. PROTECTED CHARACTERISTICS**

Sapphos prohibits discrimination, harassment, and retaliation based on
the following protected characteristics (Gov. Code § 12940):

-   **Race** (including traits historically associated with race such as
    hair texture and protective hairstyles including braids, locks, and
    twists)

-   **Color**

-   **National origin or ancestry**

-   **Citizenship status**

-   **Religion or creed** (including religious dress and grooming
    practices)

-   **Age** (40 years and older)

-   **Sex** (including pregnancy, childbirth, breastfeeding, and medical
    conditions related to pregnancy or childbirth)

-   **Gender, gender identity, and gender expression** (including
    transgender status and transitioning)

-   **Sexual orientation**

-   **Marital status** (including registered domestic partnership
    status)

-   **Military or veteran status**

-   **Disability** (physical or mental, including HIV/AIDS status,
    cancer, genetic characteristics)

-   **Medical condition** (including genetic information, cancer, and a
    record or history of cancer)

-   **Genetic information**

-   **Reproductive health decision-making** (Gov. Code § 12945.8) --
    including decisions to use or not use any drug, device, or medical
    service related to reproductive health

-   **Reproductive loss** (Gov. Code § 12945.6) -- including leave taken
    for pregnancy loss (miscarriage, stillbirth, unsuccessful IVF,
    failed adoption or surrogacy)

-   **Off-duty cannabis use** (Gov. Code § 12954) -- lawful use of
    cannabis outside the workplace away from work premises during
    non-working hours

-   **Criminal history** (arrest or conviction records, participation in
    diversion programs, expunged or sealed records)

This policy also prohibits adverse action based on:

-   **Requesting or taking protected leave** (FMLA, CFRA, pregnancy
    disability leave, sick leave, reproductive loss leave, bereavement
    leave)

-   **Filing a workers\' compensation claim**

-   **Whistleblowing or reporting legal violations**

-   **Requesting reasonable accommodation** for disability or religious
    practice

-   **Engaging in protected union activity or concerted activity**

-   **Requesting lactation accommodation**

**IV. PROHIBITED CONDUCT**

**A. Discrimination**

**Discrimination** is treating an individual or group differently in
employment decisions based on a protected characteristic.

**Prohibited discriminatory conduct includes:**

-   **Hiring or recruitment:** Refusing to hire, recruit, or interview
    based on protected status

-   **Compensation:** Paying different wages or benefits based on
    protected status

-   **Promotion or advancement:** Denying promotion opportunities based
    on protected status

-   **Job assignments:** Assigning less desirable work, projects, or
    shifts based on protected status

-   **Training and development:** Excluding from training or
    professional development based on protected status

-   **Discipline:** Imposing harsher discipline based on protected
    status

-   **Termination or layoff:** Selecting for termination based on
    protected status rather than legitimate business criteria

-   **Terms and conditions of employment:** Providing different working
    conditions, benefits, or privileges based on protected status

**Examples of discrimination:**

-   Refusing to hire women for field work positions based on assumptions
    about physical capabilities

-   Paying employees of different races different salaries for
    substantially similar work

-   Denying promotion to an employee because of their age

-   Assigning less prestigious projects to employees based on national
    origin

-   Excluding an employee from client meetings because of their
    religious attire

-   Terminating an employee shortly after learning of their disability
    or medical condition

-   Denying job applicants based on criminal history without conducting
    individualized assessment

**B. Harassment (Non-Sexual)**

**Harassment** is unwelcome conduct based on a protected characteristic
that is sufficiently severe or pervasive to create a hostile,
intimidating, or offensive work environment, or that interferes with
work performance.

A **hostile work environment** exists when harassment is severe or
pervasive enough that a reasonable person would find the work
environment intimidating, hostile, or abusive, and the victim
subjectively perceives it as such.

**Prohibited harassment includes:**

***Verbal Harassment:***

-   Slurs, epithets, or derogatory comments based on protected
    characteristics

-   Offensive jokes, insults, or name-calling

-   Negative stereotyping or generalized statements about protected
    groups

-   Mocking accent, speech patterns, or language

-   Comments about physical appearance related to protected
    characteristics

-   Repeated unwelcome social invitations after clear rejection

-   Intrusive questions about protected characteristics (e.g., religious
    practices, medical conditions, immigration status, reproductive
    choices)

***Visual Harassment:***

-   Displaying or circulating offensive images, cartoons, posters, or
    graffiti

-   Sending offensive emails, text messages, or social media posts

-   Using offensive screen savers, backgrounds, or avatars

-   Making derogatory gestures

***Physical Harassment:***

-   Unwanted touching, patting, or brushing against someone

-   Assault or threats of physical harm

-   Blocking movement or cornering someone

-   Physical intimidation (standing too close, leaning over)

-   Damaging personal property based on protected status

**Examples of non-sexual harassment:**

-   Repeatedly telling jokes mocking a coworker\'s religion or religious
    practices

-   Circulating cartoons depicting racial stereotypes

-   Making repeated negative comments about older workers being \"out of
    touch\" or \"behind the times\"

-   Mocking a coworker\'s accent or asking \"where are you really
    from?\"

-   Making derogatory comments about an employee\'s pregnancy or
    suggesting they are less committed to work

-   Asking intrusive questions about an employee\'s disability or
    medical treatment

-   Commenting negatively on an employee\'s use of reproductive health
    services or reproductive loss leave

-   Excluding an employee from team activities because of their sexual
    orientation

-   Making negative comments about an employee\'s lawful off-duty
    cannabis use

-   Repeatedly asking about criminal history after hire or making
    derogatory comments about past convictions

**C. Sexual Harassment**

**Sexual harassment** is unwelcome conduct of a sexual nature. Under
California law (Gov. Code § 12940(j)), sexual harassment includes two
types of prohibited conduct:

***1. Quid Pro Quo Sexual Harassment (\"This for That\")***

**Quid pro quo harassment** occurs when submission to or rejection of
sexual conduct is used as the basis for employment decisions affecting
an individual.

**Examples:**

-   A supervisor tells an employee that a promotion depends on going on
    a date

-   A manager suggests that an employee\'s job security depends on
    tolerating sexual advances

-   A supervisor offers preferential treatment (better assignments,
    schedule, pay) in exchange for sexual favors

-   A supervisor retaliates against an employee who rejects sexual
    advances (poor performance review, demotion, termination,
    undesirable job assignment)

-   A supervisor conditions training opportunities on acceptance of
    sexual propositions

**Key point: Even a SINGLE INCIDENT of quid pro quo harassment can
violate this policy and the law.**

***2. Hostile Work Environment Sexual Harassment***

**Hostile environment sexual harassment** occurs when unwelcome sexual
conduct is sufficiently severe or pervasive to alter the conditions of
employment and create an abusive work environment.

**Examples:**

**Verbal:** Sexual comments about appearance, body, or clothing; sexual
jokes or innuendos; sexually explicit stories; graphic descriptions of
sexual activities; repeated requests for dates after clear rejection;
making \"kissing\" or other sexual sounds; sexual nicknames or terms of
endearment; intrusive questions about sexual life, preferences, or
activities; discussing sexual conquests or experiences; rating
attractiveness or sexual desirability

**Visual:** Displaying sexually suggestive posters, calendars,
photographs, or screensavers; sending sexually explicit emails, texts,
memes, or images; making sexual gestures; staring or leering at body
parts; repeatedly looking someone up and down; displaying sexual content
on personal devices visible to others

**Physical:** Unwanted touching (hugging, kissing, patting, rubbing,
massaging); deliberately brushing against someone; blocking movement or
cornering; sexual assault or attempted assault; grabbing or groping

**Other:** Following someone; waiting for someone; giving unwanted gifts
of a romantic or sexual nature; love letters or notes after rejection;
repeated attempts to establish romantic relationship after clear
rejection

**Virtual/Remote Environment Examples:**

-   Sending sexually suggestive messages via Slack, Teams, email, or
    text

-   Making sexual comments during video calls about appearance,
    clothing, or home environment

-   Sharing sexually explicit content in group chats or channels

-   Making unwanted romantic advances via virtual communication

-   Commenting on body or appearance during video meetings

-   Using sexually suggestive virtual backgrounds or profile images

**Important Note:** Sexual harassment can occur between individuals of
any gender or sexual orientation. It can be committed by supervisors,
coworkers, clients, vendors, or any other person in connection with
work.

**D. Retaliation**

**Retaliation** is any adverse action taken against an individual
because they engaged in protected activity.

***Protected Activities Include:***

-   **Reporting** discrimination, harassment, or other violations
    (internally or to external agencies)

-   **Filing a complaint** with the California Civil Rights Department
    (CRD), Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), or other
    government agency

-   **Participating in an investigation** (as complainant, witness, or
    investigator)

-   **Opposing unlawful practices** (objecting to discriminatory
    conduct, refusing to follow discriminatory orders)

-   **Requesting reasonable accommodation** for disability or religious
    practice

-   **Taking protected leave** (FMLA, CFRA, sick leave, pregnancy
    disability leave, reproductive loss leave)

-   **Requesting lactation breaks or accommodation**

-   **Filing a workers\' compensation claim**

-   **Whistleblowing** (reporting violations of law, regulation, or
    public policy)

-   **Engaging in union activity or protected concerted activity**

***Forms of Retaliation (Examples):***

-   Termination, demotion, suspension, or other disciplinary action

-   Denial of promotion, training, or advancement opportunities

-   Negative or unjustified performance review

-   Undesirable job assignment, transfer, or schedule change

-   Reduction in hours, pay, or benefits

-   Increased scrutiny, micromanagement, or unrealistic performance
    standards

-   Exclusion from meetings, projects, or communications

-   Hostile treatment, shunning, or social isolation

-   Threats or intimidation

-   Spreading rumors or making false statements

-   Creating obstacles to performance (withholding resources,
    information, or support)

**Critical Point: Retaliation is independently unlawful even if the
underlying harassment or discrimination complaint is found to be
unsubstantiated. Making a GOOD-FAITH COMPLAINT is protected, even if the
investigation does not find a violation.**

**E. Inappropriate Conduct**

Beyond conduct that violates the law, Sapphos
discourages **inappropriate workplace conduct** that, while not
necessarily severe or pervasive enough to constitute illegal harassment,
is unprofessional and inconsistent with our values of respect and
dignity.

**Examples of inappropriate conduct:**

-   Off-color jokes or comments (even if not directed at protected
    characteristic)

-   Persistent unwelcome social invitations after polite decline

-   Comments on physical appearance unrelated to work (even if not
    sexual)

-   Gossip or rumors about coworkers\' personal lives

-   Exclusionary behavior or cliques that make coworkers feel unwelcome

-   Condescending or dismissive treatment

-   Yelling, cursing, or aggressive communication

**Employees who experience or witness inappropriate conduct are
encouraged to report it** so the Company can address issues before they
escalate to unlawful harassment. Reports of inappropriate conduct will
be handled confidentially and addressed through coaching, counseling, or
other appropriate measures.

**V. REPORTING PROCEDURES**

**A. Duty to Report**

**All employees are strongly encouraged to report** any conduct that
violates this policy or that they believe may violate this policy. **You
do not need to be certain** that a violation has occurred. If you
experience, witness, or become aware of conduct that may be
discrimination, harassment, or retaliation, please report it.

Early reporting allows the Company to investigate and address issues
before they become severe.

**B. Multiple Reporting Channels -- No Chain of Command Required**

